RABIES, RACCOONS - VACCINES (02)
================================
[see: Rabies, raccoons - vaccines: RFI 970517174911]
[1]
Date: Sun, 18 May 1997 16:55:11 -0500
From: "Dr. Craig Carter" <cncarter@TVMDL.TAMU.EDU>

There are no parenteral rabies vaccines licensed for use in wild
animals--period. Since the efficacy of rabies vaccines for wild animals
has not been measured or tested, the choice of a product is a moot point.
Because of the high risk of rabies in wild animals (especially raccoons,
skunks, coyotes, foxes and bats) the AVMA strongly suggests that these
animals not be managed, distributed or kept as pets.
Reference: Compendium of Animal Rabies Control, 1997. Journal of the
American Veterinary Medical Association, Vol 210, No. 1, January 1, 1997.
--
